      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Proponents argue that a government's legitimacy is entirely derived from its ability to define and enforce the boundaries of its jurisdiction; without the power to control who enters, the state loses its monopoly on sovereignty and becomes a mere collection of individuals without unified authority. This erosion of border control fundamentally undermines the rule of law because it allows foreign actors to bypass domestic legal systems, effectively creating a parallel set of laws that operates outside the constitution and judicial process. By failing to secure the border, the government signals that its laws are optional for certain groups, which directly weakens the moral and legal foundation upon which all other statutes rest.",
      "source": "target",
